Sometimes, the documentation doesn’t tell you everything you need to know. You need to get elbow-deep in the code

First attempt
The source code for many functions can be found by simply calling the function without parentheses.

hello_world &lt;- \() {
  print("Hello, world!")
}
hello_world()

[1] "Hello, world!"

hello_world

function () 
{
    print("Hello, world!")
}




Finding the source code for S3 and S4 methods
Generic functions, which have different methods for different classes of objects, require the specific method to be called. You can use the methods() function to see what methods are available for a generic function, and then append the method to the generic function name to see the source code for that specific method.

methods(mean)

[1] mean.Date     mean.default  mean.difftime mean.POSIXct  mean.POSIXlt 
[6] mean.quosure*
see '?methods' for accessing help and source code

mean.default

function (x, trim = 0, na.rm = FALSE, ...) 
{
    if (!is.numeric(x) && !is.complex(x) && !is.logical(x)) {
        warning("argument is not numeric or logical: returning NA")
        return(NA_real_)
    }
    if (isTRUE(na.rm)) 
        x &lt;- x[!is.na(x)]
    if (!is.numeric(trim) || length(trim) != 1L) 
        stop("'trim' must be numeric of length one")
    n &lt;- length(x)
    if (trim &gt; 0 && n) {
        if (is.complex(x)) 
            stop("trimmed means are not defined for complex data")
        if (anyNA(x)) 
            return(NA_real_)
        if (trim &gt;= 0.5) 
            return(stats::median(x, na.rm = FALSE))
        lo &lt;- floor(n * trim) + 1
        hi &lt;- n + 1 - lo
        x &lt;- sort.int(x, partial = unique(c(lo, hi)))[lo:hi]
    }
    .Internal(mean(x))
}
